rigger sharp selloff\n- **Lockup expiration**: Typical IPO lockups (90-180 days) mean insiders can sell around late September/December, creating selling pressure in August through September window\n- **Multiple compression**: Tech multiples contract if rates rise or recession concerns emerge\n- **Index fund rotation**: If Nasdaq-100 weightings become problematic (too large), forced selling\n- **xAI/X integration problems**: Execution delays, management departures, or strategic disputes\n- **Margin pressure**: Space launch margins may compress if reusability targets aren't met\n- **Market-wide tech selloff**: Broader sector rotation away from unprofitable tech\n\n## (d) What would push the value higher?\n\n- **Nasdaq-100 index inclusion boost**: The $7B forced buy on a single day (July 6) could create sustained momentum\n- **Strong revenue guidance for 2026**: Even without profitability, evidence of 30%+ revenue growth could justify higher multiples\n- **xAI AI product traction**: If X.AI's AI products (like Grok) show adoption metrics or commercial viability\n- **Satellite/constellation news**: Major Starlink customer wins or DoD/government contracts announced\n- **Broadening retail demand**: If retail investor interest remains strong post-IPO\n- **Positive comparable multiples**: If other mega-cap unprofitable tech trades at similar or higher revenue multiples\n- **Technical momentum**: IPOs often have strong technical rallies in weeks 3-8; could see 15-25% pop\n\n## (e) Base rate or historical reference values\n\n**No reliable base rate available** from specific named sources in the background material that provides historical precedent for mega-cap tech IPO price movements 60 days post-listing.\n\nHowever, I can apply general IPO and mega-cap tech dynamics:\n- Typical tech IPOs see 10-30% volatility in first 90 days\n- Mega-cap IPOs ($50B+) tend to stabilize faster than small IPOs due to institutional buying\n- Index inclusion events typically produce 3-10% price